fr: "Si chacun s'occupait de ses affaires, >> dit la Duchesse avec un grognement rauque, << le monde n'en irait que mieux.

eng: "Which would _not_ be an advantage," said Alice, who felt very glad to get an opportunity of showing off a little of her knowledge.
fr: << Ce qui ne serait guere avantageux, >> dit Alice, enchantee qu'il se presentat une occasion de montrer un peu de son savoir.

eng: "Just think of what work it would make with the day and night! You see the earth takes twenty-four hours to turn round on its axis--"
fr: Songez a ce que deviendraient le jour et la nuit ; vous voyez bien, la terre met vingt-quatre heures a faire sa revolution.

eng: "Talking of axes," said the Duchess, "chop off her head!"
fr: << Ah ! ~~~ vous parlez de faire des revolutions ! >> dit la Duchesse. ~~~ << Qu'on lui coupe la tete !

eng: "Oh, don't bother _me_," said the Duchess; "I never could abide figures!"
fr: 'laissez-moi la paix, >> dit la Duchesse, << je n'ai jamais pu souffrir les chiffres. >>

eng: And with that she began nursing her child again, singing a sort of lullaby to it as she did so, and giving it a violent shake at the end of every line:
fr: Et la-dessus elle recommenca a dorloter son enfant, lui chantant une espece de chanson pour l'endormir et lui donnant une forte secousse au bout de chaque vers.

eng: "Speak roughly to your little boy, And beat him when he sneezes: He only does it to annoy, Because he knows it teases."
fr: << Grondez-moi ce vilain garcon ! Battez-le quand il eternue ; A vous taquiner, sans facon Le mechant enfant s'evertue. >>

eng: CHORUS. (In which the cook and the baby joined): "Wow! wow! wow!"
fr: Refrain (que reprirent en choeur la cuisiniere et le bebe). << Brou, Brou, Brou ! >> (bis.)

eng: While the Duchess sang the second verse of the song, she kept tossing the baby violently up and down, and the poor little thing howled so, that Alice could hardly hear the words:--
fr: En chantant le second couplet de la chanson la Duchesse faisait sauter le bebe et le secouait violemment, si bien que le pauvre petit etre hurlait au point qu'Alice put a peine entendre ces mots :

eng: "I speak severely to my boy, I beat him when he sneezes; For he can thoroughly enjoy The pepper when he pleases!"
fr: << Oui, oui, je m'en vais le gronder, Et le battre, s'il eternue ; Car bientot a savoir poivrer, Je veux que l'enfant s'habitue. >>

eng: CHORUS. ~~~ "Wow! wow! wow!" ~~~
fr: Refrain << Brou, Brou, Brou ! >> (bis.)

eng: "Here! you may nurse it a bit, if you like!" the Duchess said to Alice, flinging the baby at her as she spoke.
fr: << Tenez, vous pouvez le dorloter si vous voulez ! >> dit la Duchesse a Alice : et a ces mots elle lui jeta le bebe.

eng: "I must go and get ready to play croquet with the Queen," and she hurried out of the room.
fr: << Il faut que j'aille m'appreter pour aller jouer au croquet avec la Reine. >> Et elle se precipita hors de la chambre.

eng: The cook threw a frying-pan after her as she went out, but it just missed her.
fr: La cuisiniere lui lanca une poele comme elle s'en allait, mais elle la manqua tout juste.

eng: Alice caught the baby with some difficulty, as it was a queer-shaped little creature, and held out its arms and legs in all directions, "just like a star-fish," thought Alice.
fr: Alice eut de la peine a attraper le bebe. C'etait un petit etre d'une forme etrange qui tenait ses bras et ses jambes etendus dans toutes les directions ; << Tout comme une etoile de mer, >> pensait Alice.

eng: I-- (No direct equivalent in text)
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: As soon as she had made out the proper way of nursing it, (which was to twist it up into a sort of knot, and then keep tight hold of its right ear and left foot, so as to prevent its undoing itself,) she carried it out into the open air.
fr: Sitot qu'elle eut trouve le bon moyen de le bercer, (qui etait d'en faire une espece de noeud, et puis de le tenir fermement par l'oreille droite et le pied gauche afin de l'empecher de se denouer,) elle le porta dehors en plein air.

eng: "If I don't take this child away with me," thought Alice, "they're sure to kill it in a day or two: wouldn't it be murder to leave it behind?"
fr: << Si je n'emporte pas cet enfant avec moi, >> pensa Alice, << ils le tueront bien sur un de ces jours. Ne serait-ce pas un meurtre de l'abandonner ? >>

eng: She said the last words out loud, and the little thing grunted in reply (it had left off sneezing by this time).
fr: Elle dit ces derniers mots a haute voix, et la petite creature repondit en grognant (elle avait cesse d'eternuer alors).

eng: "Don't grunt," said Alice; "that's not at all a proper way of expressing yourself."
fr: << Ne grogne pas ainsi, >> dit Alice ; << ce n'est pas la du tout une bonne maniere de s'exprimer. >>

eng: The baby grunted again, and Alice looked very anxiously into its face to see what was the matter with it.
fr: Le bebe grogna de nouveau. ~~~ Alice le regarda au visage avec inquietude pour voir ce qu'il avait.

eng: There could be no doubt that it had a _very_ turn-up nose, much more like a snout than a real nose; also its eyes were getting extremely small for a baby: altogether Alice did not like the look of the thing at all.
fr: Sans contredit son nez etait tres-retrousse, et ressemblait bien plutot a un groin qu'a un vrai nez. Ses yeux aussi devenaient tres-petits pour un bebe. Enfin Alice ne trouva pas du tout de son gout l'aspect de ce petit etre.

eng: "But perhaps it was only sobbing," she thought, and looked into its eyes again, to see if there were any tears.
fr: << Mais peut-etre sanglotait-il tout simplement, >> pensa-t-elle, et elle regarda de nouveau les yeux du bebe pour voir s'il n'y avait pas de larmes.

eng: No, there were no tears. "If you're going to turn into a pig, my dear," said Alice, seriously, "I'll have nothing more to do with you. Mind now!"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: The poor little thing sobbed again (or grunted, it was impossible to say which), and they went on for some while in silence.
fr: La pauvre petite creature sanglota de nouveau, ou grogna (il etait impossible de savoir lequel des deux), et ils continuerent leur chemin un instant en silence.

eng: And she began thinking over other children she knew, who might do very well as pigs, and was just saying to herself, "if one only knew the right way to change them--"
fr: >> Alors elle se mit a penser a d'autres enfants qu'elle connaissait et qui feraient d'assez jolis porcs, si seulement on savait la maniere de s'y prendre pour les metamorphoser.

eng: when she was a little startled by seeing the Cheshire Cat sitting on a bough of a tree a few yards off.
fr: Elle etait en train de faire ces reflexions, lorsqu'elle tressaillit en voyant tout a coup le Chat assis a quelques pas de la sur la branche d'un arbre.

eng: The Cat only grinned when it saw Alice.
fr: Le Chat grimaca en apercevant Alice.

eng: It looked good-natured, she thought: still it had _very_ long claws and a great many teeth, so she felt that it ought to be treated with respect.
fr: Elle trouva qu'il avait l'air bon enfant, et cependant il avait de tres-longues griffes et une grande rangee de dents ; aussi comprit-elle qu'il fallait le traiter avec respect.

eng: << Grimacon !
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "That depends a good deal on where you want to get to," said the Cat.
fr: ">> Cela depend beaucoup de l'endroit ou vous voulez aller, >> dit le Chat.

eng: "I don't much care where--" said Alice.
fr: "<< Cela m'est assez indifferent, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Then it doesn't matter which way you go," said the Cat.
fr: "<< Alors peu importe de quel cote vous irez, >> dit le Chat.

eng: "Well, then," the Cat went on, "you see, a dog growls when it's angry, and wags its tail when it's pleased. Now _I_ growl when I'm pleased, and wag my tail when I'm angry. Therefore I'm mad."
fr: "<< Eh bien ! ~~~ >> continua le Chat, << un chien grogne quand il se fache, et remue la queue lorsqu'il est content. Or, moi, je grogne quand je suis content, et je remue la queue quand je me fache. Donc je suis fou. >>

eng: "_I_ call it purring, not growling," said Alice.
fr: << J'appelle cela faire le rouet, et non pas grogner, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Call it what you like," said the Cat.
fr: << Appelez cela comme vous voudrez, >> dit le Chat.

eng: "By-the-bye, what became of the baby?" said the Cat.
fr: "<< A propos, qu'est devenu le bebe ?"

eng: "I'd nearly forgotten to ask."
fr: "J'allais oublier de le demander."

eng: Alice waited a little, half expecting to see it again, but it did not appear, and after a minute or two she walked on in the direction in which the March Hare was said to live.
fr: Alice attendit quelques instants, esperant presque le revoir, mais il ne reparut pas ; et une ou deux minutes apres, elle continua son chemin dans la direction ou on lui avait dit que demeurait le Lievre.

eng: "I've seen hatters before," she said to herself; "the March Hare will be much the most interesting, and perhaps as this is May it won't be raving mad--at least not so mad as it was in March."
fr: << J'ai deja vu des chapeliers, >> se dit-elle ; << le Lievre sera de beaucoup le plus interessant. >>

eng: As she said this, she looked up, and there was the Cat again, sitting on a branch of a tree.
fr: A ces mots elle leva les yeux, et voila que le Chat etait encore la assis sur une branche d'arbre.

eng: "Did you say pig, or fig?" said the Cat.
fr: << M'avez-vous dit porc, ou porte ? >> demanda le Chat.

eng: "I said pig," replied Alice; "and I wish you wouldn't keep appearing and vanishing so suddenly: you make one quite giddy."
fr: << J'ai dit porc, >> repeta Alice. ~~~ << Ne vous amusez donc pas a paraitre et a disparaitre si subitement, vous faites tourner la tete aux gens.

eng: "Well! ~~~ I've often seen a cat without a grin," thought Alice; "but a grin without a cat! It's the most curious thing I ever saw in my life!"
fr: "<< Certes, >> pensa Alice, << j'ai souvent vu un chat sans grimace, mais une grimace sans chat, je n'ai jamais de ma vie rien vu de si drole. >>

eng: She had not gone much farther before she came in sight of the house of the March Hare:
fr: Elle ne fit pas beaucoup de chemin avant d'arriver devant la maison du Lievre.

eng: she thought it must be the right house, because the chimneys were shaped like ears and the roof was thatched with fur.
fr: Elle pensa que ce devait bien etre la la maison, car les cheminees etaient en forme d'oreilles et le toit etait couvert de fourrure.

eng: "No room!" they cried out when they saw Alice coming.
fr: "<< Il n'y a pas de place ! Il n'y a pas de place ! >> crierent-ils en voyant Alice."

eng: "There's _plenty_ of room!" said Alice indignantly, and she sat down in a large arm-chair at one end of the table.
fr: "<< Il y a abondance de place, >> dit Alice indignee, et elle s'assit dans un large fauteuil a l'un des bouts de la table."

eng: "You should learn not to make personal remarks," Alice said with some severity; "it's very rude."
fr: "<< Vous devriez apprendre a ne pas faire de remarques sur les gens ; c'est tres-grossier, >> dit Alice d'un ton severe.

eng: The Hatter opened his eyes very wide on hearing this; but all he _said_ was, "Why is a raven like a writing-desk?"
fr: A ces mots le Chapelier ouvrit de grands yeux ; mais il se contenta de dire : << Pourquoi une pie ressemble-t-elle a un pupitre ? >>

eng: "Come, we shall have some fun now!" thought Alice.
fr: << Bon ! nous allons nous amuser, >> pensa Alice.

eng: "I'm glad they've begun asking riddles.--I believe I can guess that," she added aloud.
fr: << Je suis bien aise qu'ils se mettent a demander des enigmes. Je crois pouvoir deviner cela, >> ajouta-t-elle tout haut.

eng: "Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it?" said the March Hare.
fr: << Voulez-vous dire que vous croyez pouvoir trouver la reponse ? >> dit le Lievre.

eng: "I do," Alice hastily replied;
fr: "<< C'est ce que je fais, >> repliqua vivement Alice.

eng: "at least--at least I mean what I say--that's the same thing, you know."
fr: "<< Du moins -- je veux dire ce que je dis ; c'est la meme chose, n'est-ce pas ? >>

eng: "Not the same thing a bit!"
fr: "<< Ce n'est pas du tout la meme chose, >> dit le Chapelier.

eng: "You might just as well say that 'I see what I eat' is the same thing as 'I eat what I see'!"
fr: "<< Vous pourriez alors dire tout aussi bien que : << Je vois ce que je mange, >> est la meme chose que : << Je mange ce que je vois.>>

eng: The Hatter was the first to break the silence.
fr: Le Chapelier rompit le silence le premier.

eng: "What day of the month is it?" he said, turning to Alice:
fr: << Quel quantieme du mois sommes-nous ? >> dit-il en se tournant vers Alice.

eng: he had taken his watch out of his pocket, and was looking at it uneasily, shaking it every now and then, and holding it to his ear.
fr: Il avait tire sa montre de sa poche et la regardait d'un air inquiet, la secouant de temps a autre et l'approchant de son oreille.

eng: The March Hare took the watch and looked at it gloomily:
fr: Le Lievre prit la montre, et la contempla tristement,

eng: then he dipped it into his cup of tea, and looked at it again:
fr: puis la trempa dans sa tasse, la contempla de nouveau,

eng: but he could think of nothing better to say than his first remark, "It was the _best_ butter, you know."
fr: et pourtant ne trouva rien de mieux a faire que de repeter sa premiere observation : << C'etait tout ce qu'il y avait de plus fin en beurre. >>

eng: Alice had been looking over his shoulder with some curiosity.
fr: Alice avait regarde par-dessus son epaule avec curiosite :

eng: "What a funny watch!" she remarked.
fr: << Quelle singuliere montre ! >> dit-elle.

eng: "It tells the day of the month, and doesn't tell what o'clock it is!"
fr: << Elle marque le quantieme du mois, et ne marque pas l'heure qu'il est ! >>

eng: "Why should it?" muttered the Hatter.
fr: << Et pourquoi marquerait-elle l'heure ? >> murmura le Chapelier.

eng: "Does _your_ watch tell you what year it is?"
fr: << Votre montre marque-t-elle dans quelle annee vous etes ? >>

eng: "Of course not," Alice replied very readily:
fr: << Non, assurement ! >> repliqua Alice sans hesiter.

eng: "but that's because it stays the same year for such a long time together."
fr: << Mais c'est parce qu'elle reste a la meme annee pendant si longtemps.

eng: "If you knew Time as well as I do," said the Hatter, "you wouldn't talk about wasting _it_. It's _him_."
fr: '>> Si vous connaissiez le Temps aussi bien que moi, >> dit le Chapelier, << vous ne parleriez pas de le gaspiller. On ne gaspille pas quelqu'un. >>

eng: "I don't know what you mean," said Alice.
fr: << Je ne vous comprends pas, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Of course you don't!" ~~~ the Hatter said, tossing his head contemptuously. ~~~ "I dare say you never even spoke to Time!"
fr: << Je le crois bien, >> repondit le Chapelier, en secouant la tete avec mepris ; << je parie que vous n'avez jamais parle au Temps. >>

eng: "Perhaps not," Alice cautiously replied: "but I know I have to beat time when I learn music."
fr: << Cela se peut bien, >> repliqua prudemment Alice, << mais je l'ai souvent mal employe. >>

eng: "Ah! that accounts for it," said the Hatter.
fr: << Ah ! voila donc pourquoi ! Il n'aime pas cela, >> dit le Chapelier.

eng: "He won't stand beating. Now, if you only kept on good terms with him, he'd do almost anything you liked with the clock. For instance, suppose it were nine o'clock in the morning, just time to begin lessons: you'd only have to whisper a hint to Time, and round goes the clock in a twinkling! ~~~ Half-past one, time for dinner!"
fr: << Mais si seulement vous saviez le menager, il ferait de la pendule tout ce que vous voudriez. Par exemple, supposons qu'il soit neuf heures du matin, l'heure de vos lecons, vous n'auriez qu'a dire tout bas un petit mot au Temps, et l'aiguille partirait en un clin d'oeil pour marquer une heure et demie, l'heure du diner. >>

eng: ("I only wish it was," the March Hare said to itself in a whisper.)
fr: (<< Je le voudrais bien, >> dit tout bas le Lievre.)

eng: "That would be grand, certainly," said Alice thoughtfully: "but then--I shouldn't be hungry for it, you know."'
fr: << Cela serait tres-agreable, certainement, >> dit Alice d'un air pensif ; << mais alors -- je n'aurais pas encore faim, comprenez donc.'

eng: The Hatter shook his head mournfully.
fr: Le Chapelier secoua tristement la tete.

eng: "Not I!" he replied.
fr: << Helas ! non, >> repondit-il,

eng: "We quarrelled last March--just before _he_ went mad, you know--" (pointing with his tea spoon at the March Hare,)
fr: << nous nous sommes querelles au mois de mars dernier, un peu avant qu'il devint fou. ~~~ >> (Il montrait le Lievre du bout de sa cuiller.)

eng: "--it was at the great concert given by the Queen of Hearts, and I had to sing 'Twinkle, twinkle, little bat! How I wonder what you're at!'"
fr: << C'etait a un grand concert donne par la Reine de Coeur, et j'eus a chanter : << Ah ! vous dirai-je, ma soeur, Ce qui calme ma douleur ! >>

eng: You know the song, perhaps?"
fr: << Vous connaissez peut-etre cette chanson ? >>

eng: "I've heard something like it," said Alice.
fr: << J'ai entendu chanter quelque chose comme ca, >> dit Alice.

eng: "It goes on, you know," the Hatter continued, "in this way:-- 'Up above the world you fly, Like a tea-tray in the sky. Twinkle, twinkle--'"
fr: << Vous savez la suite, >> dit le Chapelier ; et il continua : << C'est que j'avais des dragees, Et que je les ai mangees. >>

eng: Here the Dormouse shook itself, and began singing in its sleep "_Twinkle, twinkle, twinkle, twinkle_--"
fr: Ici le Loir se secoua et se mit a chanter, tout en dormant : << Et que je les ai mangees, mangees, mangees, mangees, mangees, >>

eng: and went on so long that they had to pinch it to make it stop.'
fr: si longtemps, qu'il fallut le pincer pour le faire taire.

eng: "And ever since that," the Hatter went on in a mournful tone, "he won't do a thing I ask! It's always six o'clock now."
fr: '<< Et, depuis lors, >> continua le Chapelier avec tristesse, << le Temps ne veut rien faire de ce que je lui demande. Il est toujours six heures maintenant. >>

eng: A bright idea came into Alice's head.
fr: Une brillante idee traversa l'esprit d'Alice.

eng: "Yes, that's it," said the Hatter with a sigh: "it's always tea-time, and we've no time to wash the things between whiles."
fr: "<< Oui, c'est cela, >> dit le Chapelier avec un soupir ; << il est toujours l'heure du the, et nous n'avons pas le temps de laver la vaisselle dans l'intervalle. >>

eng: "Then you keep moving round, I suppose?" said Alice.
fr: "<< Alors vous faites tout le tour de la table, je suppose ? >> dit Alice."

eng: "Exactly so," said the Hatter: "as the things get used up."
fr: "<< Justement, >> dit le Chapelier, << a mesure que les tasses ont servi. >>

eng: "But what happens when you come to the beginning again?" Alice ventured to ask.
fr: "<< Mais, qu'arrive-t-il lorsque vous vous retrouvez au commencement ? >> se hasarda de dire Alice."

eng: "Suppose we change the subject," the March Hare interrupted, yawning. "I'm getting tired of this. I vote the young lady tells us a story."
fr: "<< Si nous changions de conversation, >> interrompit le Lievre en baillant ; << celle-ci commence a me fatiguer. Je propose que la petite demoiselle nous conte une histoire. >>

eng: "I'm afraid I don't know one," said Alice, rather alarmed at the proposal.
fr: "<< J'ai bien peur de n'en pas savoir, >> dit Alice, que cette proposition alarmait un peu."

eng: "They lived on treacle," said the Dormouse, after thinking a minute or two.
fr: '<< Elles vivaient de melasse, >> dit le Loir, apres avoir reflechi un instant.

eng: "They couldn't have done that, you know," Alice gently remarked; "they'd have been ill."
fr: << Ce n'est pas possible, comprenez donc, >> fit doucement observer Alice ; << cela les aurait rendues malades. >>

eng: "So they were," said the Dormouse; "_very_ ill."
fr: << Et en effet, >> dit le Loir, << elles etaient tres-malades. >>

eng: Alice tried to fancy to herself what such an extraordinary ways of living would be like, but it puzzled her too much, so she went on: "But why did they live at the bottom of a well?"
fr: Alice chercha a se figurer un peu l'effet que produirait sur elle une maniere de vivre si extraordinaire, mais cela lui parut trop embarrassant, et elle continua : << Mais pourquoi vivaient-elles au fond d'un puits ?

eng: "You mean you can't take _less_," said the Hatter: "it's very easy to take _more_ than nothing."
fr: '>> << Vous voulez dire que vous ne pouvez pas en prendre moins, >> dit le Chapelier. ~~~ << Il est tres-aise de prendre un peu plus que pas du tout. >>

eng: "Nobody asked _your_ opinion," said Alice.
fr: << On ne vous a pas demande votre avis, a vous, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Who's making personal remarks now?" the Hatter asked triumphantly.
fr: << Ah ! qui est-ce qui se permet de faire des observations ? >> demanda le Chapelier d'un air triomphant.

eng: Alice did not quite know what to say to this: so she helped herself to some tea and bread-and-butter, and then turned to the Dormouse, and repeated her question.
fr: Alice ne savait pas trop que repondre a cela. Aussi se servit-elle un peu de the et une tartine de pain et de beurre ; puis elle se tourna du cote du Loir, et repeta sa question.

eng: "There's no such thing!" Alice was beginning very angrily,
fr: '>> << Il n'en existe pas ! >> se mit a dire Alice d'un ton courrouce.

eng: but the Hatter and the March Hare went "Sh! sh!"
fr: ~~~ Mais le Chapelier et le Lievre firent << Chut ! Chut ! >>

eng: and the Dormouse sulkily remarked, "If you can't be civil, you'd better finish the story for yourself."
fr: et le Loir fit observer d'un ton bourru : << Tachez d'etre polie, ou finissez l'histoire vous-meme. >>

eng: "No, please go on!" Alice said very humbly;
fr: << Non, continuez, je vous prie, >> dit Alice tres-humblement.

eng: "I won't interrupt again. I dare say there may be _one_."
fr: << Je ne vous interromprai plus ; peut-etre en existe-t-il un. >>

eng: "One, indeed!" said the Dormouse indignantly.
fr: << Un, vraiment ! >> dit le Loir avec indignation ;

eng: However, he consented to go on.
fr: toutefois il voulut bien continuer.

eng: "And so these three little sisters--they were learning to draw, you know--"
fr: << Donc, ces trois petites soeurs, vous saurez qu'elles faisaient tout ce qu'elles pouvaient pour s'en tirer. >>

eng: "What did they draw?" said Alice, quite forgetting her promise.
fr: << Comment auraient-elles pu s'en tirer ? >> dit Alice, oubliant tout a fait sa promesse.

eng: "Treacle," said the Dormouse, without considering at all this time.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "I want a clean cup," interrupted the Hatter:
fr: << Il me faut une tasse propre, >> interrompit le Chapelier.

eng: "let's all move one place on."'
fr: << Avancons tous d'une place.'

eng: Alice did not wish to offend the Dormouse again, so she began very cautiously: "But I don't understand. Where did they draw the treacle from?"
fr: Alice, craignant d'offenser le Loir, reprit avec circonspection : << Mais je ne comprends pas ; comment auraient-elles pu s'en tirer ? >>

eng: "You can draw water out of a water-well," said the Hatter; "so I should think you could draw treacle out of a treacle-well--eh, stupid?"
fr: << C'est tout simple, >> dit le Chapelier. << Quand il y a de l'eau dans un puits, vous savez bien comment on en tire, n'est-ce pas ? Eh bien ! d'un puits de melasse on tire de la melasse, et quand il y a des petites filles dans la melasse on les tire en meme temps ; comprenez-vous, petite sotte ? >>

eng: "But they were _in_ the well," Alice said to the Dormouse, not choosing to notice this last remark.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Of course they were," said the Dormouse; "--well in."
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: This answer so confused poor Alice, that she let the Dormouse go on for some time without interrupting it.
fr: << Pas tout a fait, >> dit Alice, encore plus embarrassee par cette reponse.

eng: "They were learning to draw," the Dormouse went on, yawning and rubbing its eyes, for it was getting very sleepy; "and they drew all manner of things--everything that begins with an M--"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Why with an M?" said Alice.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Why not?" said the March Hare.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: Alice was silent.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: The Dormouse had closed its eyes by this time, and was going off into a doze; but, on being pinched by the Hatter, it woke up again with a little shriek, and went on: "--that begins with an M, such as mouse-traps, and the moon, and memory, and muchness--you know you say things are "much of a muchness"--did you ever see such a thing as a drawing of a muchness?"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Really, now you ask me," said Alice, very much confused, "I don't think--"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Then you shouldn't talk," said the Hatter.
fr: << Alors vous feriez bien de vous taire, >> dit le Chapelier.

eng: This piece of rudeness was more than Alice could bear: she got up in great disgust, and walked off;
fr: Alice trouva cette grossierete un peu trop forte ; elle se leva indignee et s'en alla.

eng: the Dormouse fell asleep instantly, and neither of the others took the least notice of her going, though she looked back once or twice, half hoping that they would call after her: the last time she saw them, they were trying to put the Dormouse into the teapot.
fr: Le Loir s'endormit a l'instant meme, et les deux autres ne prirent pas garde a son depart, bien qu'elle regardat en arriere deux ou trois fois, esperant presque qu'ils la rappelleraient. La derniere fois qu'elle les vit, ils cherchaient a mettre le Loir dans la theiere.

eng: "At any rate I'll never go _there_ again!" said Alice as she picked her way through the wood.
fr: << A aucun prix je ne voudrais retourner aupres de ces gens-la, >> dit Alice, en cherchant son chemin a travers le bois.

eng: "It's the stupidest tea-party I ever was at in all my life!"
fr: << C'est le the le plus ridicule auquel j'aie assiste de ma vie ! >>

eng: Just as she said this, she noticed that one of the trees had a door leading right into it.
fr: Comme elle disait cela, elle s'apercut qu'un des arbres avait une porte par laquelle on pouvait penetrer a l'interieur.

eng: "Always lay the blame on others!"
fr: 'Jetez toujours le blame sur les autres !'

eng: "_You'd_ better not talk!"
fr: 'Vous feriez bien de vous taire, vous,'

eng: "I heard the Queen say only yesterday you deserved to be beheaded!"
fr: 'J'ai entendu la Reine dire pas plus tard que hier que vous meritiez d'etre decapite !'

eng: "What for?"
fr: 'Pourquoi donc cela ?'

eng: "That's none of _your_ business, Two!"
fr: 'Cela ne vous regarde pas, Deux,'

eng: "Yes, it _is_ his business!"
fr: 'Si fait, cela le regarde,'

eng: "and I'll tell him--it was for bringing the cook tulip-roots instead of onions."
fr: 'et je vais le lui dire. C'est pour avoir apporte a la cuisiniere des oignons de tulipe au lieu d'oignons a manger.'

eng: The Queen turned crimson with fury, and, after glaring at her for a moment like a wild beast, screamed "Off with her head! Off--"
fr: La Reine devint pourpre de colere ; et apres l'avoir consideree un moment avec des yeux flamboyants comme ceux d'une bete fauve, elle se mit a crier : << Qu'on lui coupe la tete ! >>

eng: "Nonsense!" said Alice, very loudly and decidedly,
fr: << Quelle idee ! >> dit Alice tres-haut et d'un ton decide.

eng: and the Queen was silent.
fr: La Reine se tut.

eng: The three soldiers wandered about for a minute or two, looking for them, and then quietly marched off after the others.
fr: Les trois soldats errerent de cote et d'autre, pendant une ou deux minutes, pour les chercher, puis s'en allerent tranquillement rejoindre les autres.

eng: "Are their heads off?" shouted the Queen.
fr: << Leur a-t-on coupe la tete ? >> cria la Reine.

eng: "Can you play croquet?"
fr: "<< Savez-vous jouer au croquet ? >>"

eng: The soldiers were silent, and looked at Alice, as the question was evidently meant for her.
fr: Les soldats ne soufflerent mot, et regarderent Alice, car, evidemment, c'etait a elle que s'adressait la question.

eng: "Yes!" shouted Alice.
fr: "<< Oui, >> cria Alice."

eng: "Come on, then!"
fr: "<< Eh bien, venez !'"

eng: "It's--it's a very fine day!"
fr: "<< Il fait un bien beau temps aujourd'hui, >>"

eng: said a timid voice at her side.
fr: dit une voix timide a cote d'elle.

eng: She was walking by the White Rabbit, who was peeping anxiously into her face.
fr: Elle marchait aupres du Lapin Blanc, qui la regardait d'un oeil inquiet.

eng: "Very," said Alice: "--where's the Duchess?"
fr: "<< Bien beau, >> dit Alice. ~~~ << Ou est la Duchesse ?"

eng: "Hush!" said the Rabbit in a low, hurried tone.
fr: 'Chut ! >> dit vivement le Lapin a voix basse et en regardant avec inquietude par-dessus son epaule.

eng: He looked anxiously over his shoulder as he spoke, and then raised himself upon tiptoe, put his mouth close to her ear, and whispered "She's under sentence of execution."
fr: Puis il se leva sur la pointe des pieds, colla sa bouche a l'oreille d'Alice et lui souffla : << Elle est condamnee a mort >>

eng: "What for?" said Alice.
fr: << Pour quelle raison ? >> dit Alice.

eng: "Did you say 'What a pity!'?" the Rabbit asked.
fr: << Avez-vous dit : << quel dommage ? >> >> demanda le Lapin.

eng: "No, I didn't," said Alice: "I don't think it's at all a pity. I said 'What for?'"
fr: << Non, >> dit Alice. ~~~ << Je ne pense pas du tout que ce soit dommage. J'ai dit : << pour quelle raison ? >> >>

eng: "She boxed the Queen's ears--" the Rabbit began.
fr: << Elle a donne des soufflets a la Reine, >> commenca le Lapin.

eng: Alice gave a little scream of laughter.
fr: (Alice fit entendre un petit eclat de rire.)

eng: "Oh, hush!"
fr: << Oh, chut !'

eng: "Not at all," said Alice: "she's so extremely--"
fr: "<< Pas du tout, >> dit Alice.

eng: Just then she noticed that the Queen was close behind her, listening: so she went on, "--likely to win, that it's hardly worth while finishing the game."
fr: "<< Elle est si -- >> Au meme instant elle apercut la Reine tout pres derriere elle, qui ecoutait ; alors elle continua : << si sure de gagner, que ce n'est guere la peine de finir la partie. >>

eng: The Queen smiled and passed on.
fr: La Reine sourit et passa.

eng: "Who _are_ you talking to?" said the King, going up to Alice, and looking at the Cat's head with great curiosity.
fr: << Avec qui causez-vous donc la, >> dit le Roi, s'approchant d'Alice et regardant avec une extreme curiosite la tete du Chat.

eng: "It's a friend of mine--a Cheshire Cat," said Alice: "allow me to introduce it."
fr: << C'est un de mes amis, un Grimacon, >> dit Alice : << permettez-moi de vous le presenter. >>

eng: "I don't like the look of it at all," said the King:
fr: << Sa mine ne me plait pas du tout, >> dit le Roi.

eng: "however, it may kiss my hand if it likes."
fr: << Pourtant il peut me baiser la main, si cela lui fait plaisir. >>

eng: "I'd rather not," the Cat remarked.
fr: << Non, grand merci, >> dit le Chat.

eng: "Don't be impertinent," said the King, "and don't look at me like that!"
fr: << Ne faites pas l'impertinent, >> dit le Roi, << et ne me regardez pas ainsi !

eng: CHAPTER IX. The Mock Turtle's Story
fr: CHAPITRE IX. HISTOIRE DE LA FAUSSE-TORTUE.

eng: "You can't think how glad I am to see you again, you dear old thing!"
fr: "<< Vous ne sauriez croire combien je suis heureuse de vous voir, ma bonne vieille fille !"

eng: "Ah, well! It means much the same thing," said the Duchess, digging her sharp little chin into Alice's shoulder as she added, "and the moral of _that_ is--'Take care of the sense, and the sounds will take care of themselves.'"
fr: '>> << Eh bien ! Cela signifie presque la meme chose, >> dit la Duchesse, qui enfonca son petit menton pointu dans l'epaule d'Alice, en ajoutant : << Et la morale en est : << Un chien vaut mieux que deux gros rats. >> >>'

eng: "How fond she is of finding morals in things!"
fr: '<< Comme elle aime a trouver des morales partout !'

eng: "It's a mineral, I _think_," said Alice.
fr: '>> << C'est un mineral, je crois, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Of course it is," said the Duchess, who seemed ready to agree to everything that Alice said; "there's a large mustard-mine near here.
fr: << Assurement, >> dit la Duchesse, qui semblait prete a approuver tout ce que disait Alice ; << il y a une bonne mine de moutarde pres d'ici ;

eng: And the moral of that is--'The more there is of mine, the less there is of yours.'"
fr: la morale en est qu'il faut faire bonne mine a tout le monde ! >>

eng: "Oh, I know!" exclaimed Alice, who had not attended to this last remark, "it's a vegetable. It doesn't look like one, but it is."
fr: << Oh ! je sais, >> s'ecria Alice, qui n'avait pas fait attention a cette derniere observation, << c'est un vegetal ; ca n'en a pas l'air, mais c'en est un. >>

eng: "I quite agree with you," said the Duchess; "and the moral of that is--'Be what you would seem to be'--or if you'd like it put more simply--'Never imagine yourself not to be otherwise than what it might appear to others that what you were or might have been was not otherwise than what you had been would have appeared to them to be otherwise.'"
fr: << Je suis tout a fait de votre avis, >> dit la Duchesse, << et la morale en est : << Soyez ce que vous voulez paraitre ; >> ou, si vous voulez que je le dise plus simplement : << Ne vous imaginez jamais de ne pas etre autrement que ce qu'il pourrait sembler aux autres que ce que vous etiez ou auriez pu etre n'etait pas autrement que ce que vous aviez ete leur aurait paru etre autrement.'

eng: "That's nothing to what I could say if I chose," the Duchess replied, in a pleased tone.
fr: ">> << Cela n'est rien aupres de ce que je pourrais dire si je voulais, >> repondit la Duchesse d'un ton satisfait.

eng: "Pray don't trouble yourself to say it any longer than that," said Alice.
fr: << Je vous en prie, ne vous donnez pas la peine d'allonger davantage votre explication, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Oh, don't talk about trouble!" said the Duchess.
fr: << Oh ! ne parlez pas de ma peine, >> dit la Duchesse ;

eng: "I make you a present of everything I've said as yet."
fr: << je vous fais cadeau de tout ce que j'ai dit jusqu'a present. >>

eng: "A cheap sort of present!"
fr: << Voila un cadeau qui n'est pas cher !

eng: "the Duchess asked, with another dig of her sharp little chin."
fr: ">> demanda la Duchesse, avec un nouveau coup de son petit menton pointu."

eng: ""I've a right to think," said Alice sharply, for she was beginning to feel a little worried."
fr: "<< J'ai bien le droit de reflechir, >> dit Alice sechement, car elle commencait a se sentir un peu ennuyee."

eng: ""Just about as much right," said the Duchess, "as pigs have to fly; and the m--""
fr: "<< A peu pres le meme droit, >> dit la Duchesse, << que les cochons de voler, et la mo-- >>"

eng: "But here, to Alice's great surprise, the Duchess's voice died away, even in the middle of her favourite word 'moral,' and the arm that was linked into hers began to tremble."
fr: "Mais ici, au grand etonnement d'Alice, la voix de la Duchesse s'eteignit au milieu de son mot favori, morale, et le bras qui etait passe sous le sien commenca de trembler."

eng: "Now, I give you fair warning," shouted the Queen, stamping on the ground as she spoke;
fr: "<< Je vous en previens ! ~~~ >> cria la Reine, trepignant tout le temps.

eng: "either you or your head must be off, and that in about half no time! Take your choice!"
fr: "<< Hors d'ici, ou a bas la tete ! et cela en moins de rien ! Choisissez. ~~~ >>

eng: The Duchess took her choice, and was gone in a moment.
fr: La Duchesse eut bientot fait son choix : elle disparut en un clin d'oeil.

eng: "It's the thing Mock Turtle Soup is made from," said the Queen.
fr: '>> << C'est ce dont on fait la soupe a la Fausse-Tortue, >> dit la Reine.

eng: "I never saw one, or heard of one," said Alice.
fr: << Je n'en ai jamais vu, et c'est la premiere fois que j'en entends parler, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Come on, then," said the Queen, "and he shall tell you his history,"
fr: << Eh bien ! venez, >> dit la Reine, << et elle vous contera son histoire.

eng: "As they walked off together, Alice heard the King say in a low voice, to the company generally, "You are all pardoned."'
fr: >> Comme elles s'en allaient ensemble, Alice entendit le Roi dire a voix basse a toute la compagnie : << Vous etes tous gracies.

eng: (If you don't know what a Gryphon is, look at the picture.)
fr: (Si vous ne savez pas ce que c'est qu'un Griffon, regardez l'image.)

eng: "Up, lazy thing!" said the Queen, "and take this young lady to see the Mock Turtle, and to hear his history."
fr: "<< Debout ! paresseux, >> dit la Reine, << et menez cette petite demoiselle voir la Fausse-Tortue, et l'entendre raconter son histoire.'

eng: The Gryphon sat up and rubbed its eyes: then it watched the Queen till she was out of sight: then it chuckled.
fr: Le Griffon se leva et se frotta les yeux, puis il guetta la Reine jusqu'a ce qu'elle fut disparue ; et il se mit a ricaner.

eng: "What fun!" said the Gryphon, half to itself, half to Alice.
fr: << Quelle farce ! >> dit le Griffon, moitie a part soi, moitie a Alice.

eng: "What _is_ the fun?" said Alice.
fr: << Quelle est la farce ? >> demanda Alice.

eng: "Why, _she_," said the Gryphon.
fr: << Elle ! ~~~ >> dit le Griffon.

eng: "It's all her fancy, that: they never executes nobody, you know. Come on!"
fr: << C'est une idee qu'elle se fait ; jamais on n'execute personne, vous comprenez. Venez donc ! >>

eng: "Everybody says 'come on!' here," thought Alice, as she went slowly after it:
fr: << Tout le monde ici dit : << Venez donc ! >> >> pensa Alice, en suivant lentement le Griffon.

eng: "I never was so ordered about in all my life, never!"
fr: << Jamais de ma vie on ne m'a fait aller comme cela ; non, jamais ! >>

eng: They had not gone far before they saw the Mock Turtle in the distance, sitting sad and lonely on a little ledge of rock, and, as they came nearer, Alice could hear him sighing as if his heart would break.
fr: Ils ne firent pas beaucoup de chemin avant d'apercevoir dans l'eloignement la Fausse-Tortue assise, triste et solitaire, sur un petit recif, et, a mesure qu'ils approchaient, Alice pouvait l'entendre qui soupirait comme si son coeur allait se briser ;

eng: She pitied him deeply.
fr: elle la plaignait sincerement.

eng: "What is his sorrow?" she asked the Gryphon,
fr: << Quel est donc son chagrin ? >> demanda-t-elle au Griffon ;

eng: and the Gryphon answered, very nearly in the same words as before, "It's all his fancy, that: he hasn't got no sorrow, you know.
fr: et le Griffon repondit, presque dans les memes termes qu'auparavant : << C'est une idee qu'elle se fait ; elle n'a point de chagrin, vous comprenez.

eng: So they went up to the Mock Turtle, who looked at them with large eyes full of tears, but said nothing.
fr: Ainsi ils s'approcherent de la Fausse-Tortue, qui les regarda avec de grands yeux pleins de larmes, mais ne dit rien.

eng: "This here young lady," said the Gryphon, "she wants for to know your history, she do."
fr: << Cette petite demoiselle, >> dit le Griffon, << veut savoir votre histoire. >>

eng: "I'll tell it her," said the Mock Turtle in a deep, hollow tone: "sit down, both of you, and don't speak a word till I've finished."
fr: << Je vais la lui raconter, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue, d'un ton grave et sourd : << Asseyez-vous tous deux, et ne dites pas un mot avant que j'aie fini. >>

eng: So they sat down, and nobody spoke for some minutes.
fr: Ils s'assirent donc, et pendant quelques minutes, personne ne dit mot.

eng: Alice thought to herself, "I don't see how he can _ever_ finish, if he doesn't begin."
fr: Alice pensait : << Je ne vois pas comment elle pourra jamais finir si elle ne commence pas. >>

eng: But she waited patiently.
fr: Mais elle attendit patiemment.

eng: "When we were little," the Mock Turtle went on at last, more calmly, though still sobbing a little now and then, "we went to school in the sea.
fr: "<< Quand nous etions petits, >> continua la Fausse Tortue d'un ton plus calme, quoiqu'elle laissat encore de temps a autre echapper un sanglot, << nous allions a l'ecole au fond de la mer.

eng: The master was an old Turtle--we used to call him Tortoise--"
fr: La maitresse etait une vieille tortue ; nous l'appelions Chelonee.

eng: "Why did you call him Tortoise, if he wasn't one?" Alice asked.
fr: << Et pourquoi l'appeliez-vous Chelonee, si ce n'etait pas son nom ? >>

eng: "We called him Tortoise because he taught us," said the Mock Turtle angrily: "really you are very dull!"
fr: << Parce qu'on ne pouvait s'empecher de s'ecrier en la voyant : << Quel long nez ! ~~~ >> >> dit la Fausse-Tortue d'un ton fache ; << vous etes vraiment bien bornee ! >>

eng: "You ought to be ashamed of yourself for asking such a simple question," added the Gryphon; and then they both sat silent and looked at poor Alice, who felt ready to sink into the earth.
fr: << Vous devriez avoir honte de faire une question si simple ! ~~~ >> ajouta le Griffon ; et puis tous deux garderent le silence, les yeux fixes sur la pauvre Alice, qui se sentait prete a rentrer sous terre.

eng: At last the Gryphon said to the Mock Turtle, "Drive on, old fellow! Don't be all day about it!"
fr: Enfin le Griffon dit a la Fausse-Tortue, << En avant, camarade ! Tachez d'en finir aujourd'hui ! >>

eng: and he went on in these words: "Yes, we went to school in the sea, though you mayn't believe it--"
fr: et elle continua en ces termes : << Oui, nous allions a l'ecole dans la mer, bien que cela vous etonne. >>

eng: "I never said I didn't!" interrupted Alice.
fr: << Je n'ai pas dit cela, >> interrompit Alice.

eng: "You did," said the Mock Turtle.
fr: << Vous l'avez dit, >> repondit la Fausse-Tortue.

eng: "Hold your tongue!" added the Gryphon, before Alice could speak again.
fr: << Taisez-vous donc, >> ajouta le Griffon, avant qu'Alice put reprendre la parole.

eng: The Mock Turtle went on. "We had the best of educations--in fact, we went to school every day--"
fr: La Fausse-Tortue continua : << Nous recevions la meilleure education possible ; au fait, nous allions tous les jours a l'ecole. >>

eng: "_I've_ been to a day-school, too," said Alice; "you needn't be so proud as all that."
fr: << Moi aussi, j'y ai ete tous les jours, >> dit Alice ; << il n'y a pas de quoi etre si fiere. >>

eng: "With extras?" asked the Mock Turtle a little anxiously.
fr: << Avec des << en sus, >> >> dit la Fausse-Tortue avec quelque inquietude.

eng: "Yes," said Alice, "we learned French and music."
fr: << Oui, >> dit Alice, << nous apprenions l'italien et la musique en sus. >>

eng: "And washing?" said the Mock Turtle.
fr: << Et le blanchissage ? >> dit la Fausse-Tortue.

eng: "You couldn't have wanted it much," said Alice; "living at the bottom of the sea."
fr: '>> >> << Vous ne deviez pas en avoir grand besoin, puisque vous viviez au fond de la mer, >> dit Alice.'

eng: "I couldn't afford to learn it." said the Mock Turtle with a sigh.
fr: '<< Je n'avais pas les moyens de l'apprendre, >> dit en soupirant la Fausse-Tortue ;'

eng: "I only took the regular course."
fr: '<< je ne suivais que les cours ordinaires. >>'

eng: "What was that?" inquired Alice.
fr: '<< Qu'est-ce que c'etait ? >> demanda Alice.'

eng: "Reeling and Writhing, of course, to begin with," the Mock Turtle replied; "and then the different branches of Arithmetic--Ambition, Distraction, Uglification, and Derision."
fr: '<< A Luire et a Medire, cela va sans dire, >> repondit la Fausse-Tortue ; << et puis les differentes branches de l'Arithmetique : l'Ambition, la Distraction, l'Enjolification, et la Derision. >>'

eng: "I never heard of 'Uglification,'" Alice ventured to say.
fr: '<< Je n'ai jamais entendu parler d'enjolification, >> se hasarda de dire Alice.'

eng: "What is it?"
fr: '<< Qu'est-ce que c'est ? >>'

eng: The Gryphon lifted up both its paws in surprise.
fr: 'Le Griffon leva les deux pattes en l'air en signe d'etonnement.'

eng: "What! Never heard of uglifying!" it exclaimed.
fr: '<< Vous n'avez jamais entendu parler d'enjolir ! >> s'ecria-t-il.'

eng: "You know what to beautify is, I suppose?"
fr: '<< Vous savez ce que c'est que << embellir, >> je suppose ?'

eng: "Yes," said Alice doubtfully: "it means--to--make--anything--prettier."
fr: '<< Oui, >> dit Alice, en hesitant : << cela veut dire -- rendre -- une chose -- plus belle. >>'

eng: "Well, then," the Gryphon went on, "if you don't know what to uglify is, you _are_ a simpleton."
fr: '<< Eh bien ! ~~~ >> continua le Griffon, << si vous ne savez pas ce que c'est que << enjolir >> vous etes vraiment niaise. >>'

eng: Alice did not feel encouraged to ask any more questions about it, so she turned to the Mock Turtle, and said "What else had you to learn?"
fr: 'Alice ne se sentit pas encouragee a faire de nouvelles questions la-dessus, elle se tourna donc vers la Fausse-Tortue, et lui dit, << Qu'appreniez-vous encore ? >>'

eng: "Well, there was Mystery," the Mock Turtle replied, counting off the subjects on his flappers, "--Mystery, ancient and modern, with Seaography: then Drawling--the Drawling-master was an old conger-eel, that used to come once a week: _he_ taught us Drawling, Stretching, and Fainting in Coils."
fr: '<< Eh bien, il y avait le Grimoire, >> repondit la Fausse-Tortue en comptant sur ses battoirs ; << le Grimoire ancien et moderne, avec la Merographie, et puis le Dedain ; le maitre de Dedain etait un vieux congre qui venait une fois par semaine ; il nous enseignait a Dedaigner, a Esquiver et a Feindre a l'huitre. >>'

eng: "What was _that_ like?" said Alice.
fr: '<< Qu'est-ce que cela ? >> dit Alice.'

eng: "Hadn't time," said the Gryphon: "I went to the Classics master, though. He was an old crab, _he_ was."
fr: ">> Je n'en avais pas le temps, >> dit le Griffon, << mais j'ai suivi les cours du professeur de langues mortes ; c'etait un vieux crabe, celui-la. >>

eng: "I never went to him," the Mock Turtle said with a sigh: "he taught Laughing and Grief, they used to say."
fr: ">> Je n'ai jamais suivi ses cours, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue avec un soupir ; << il enseignait le Larcin et la Greve. >>

eng: "So he did, so he did," said the Gryphon, sighing in his turn; and both creatures hid their faces in their paws.
fr: ">> C'est ca, c'est ca, >> dit le Griffon, en soupirant a son tour ; et ces deux creatures se cacherent la figure dans leurs pattes."

eng: "And how did you manage on the twelfth?" Alice went on eagerly.
fr: '<< Et comment vous arrangiez-vous le douzieme jour ? >> s'empressa de demander Alice.

eng: "That's enough about lessons," the Gryphon interrupted in a very decided tone: "tell her something about the games now."
fr: << En voila assez sur les lecons, >> dit le Griffon intervenant d'un ton tres-decide ; << parlez-lui des jeux maintenant. >>

eng: CHAPTER X. The Lobster Quadrille
fr: CHAPITRE X. LE QUADRILLE DE HOMARDS.

eng: The Mock Turtle sighed deeply, and drew the back of one flapper across his eyes.
fr: La Fausse-Tortue soupira profondement et passa le dos d'une de ses nageoires sur ses yeux.

eng: He looked at Alice, and tried to speak, but for a minute or two sobs choked his voice.
fr: Elle regarda Alice et s'efforca de parler, mais les sanglots etoufferent sa voix pendant une ou deux minutes.

eng: "Same as if he had a bone in his throat," said the Gryphon: and it set to work shaking him and punching him in the back.
fr: << On dirait qu'elle a un os dans le gosier, >> dit le Griffon, et il se mit a la secouer et a lui taper dans le dos.

eng: At last the Mock Turtle recovered his voice, and, with tears running down his cheeks, he went on again:--
fr: Enfin la Fausse-Tortue retrouva la voix, et, tandis que de grosses larmes coulaient le long de ses joues, elle continua :

eng: "You may not have lived much under the sea--"
fr: << Peut-etre n'avez-vous pas beaucoup vecu au fond de la mer ? >>

eng: ("I haven't," said Alice)
fr: -- ( << Non, >> dit Alice)

eng: "--and perhaps you were never even introduced to a lobster--"
fr: << et peut-etre ne vous a-t-on jamais presentee a un homard ? >>

eng: (Alice began to say "I once tasted--" but checked herself hastily, and said "No, never")
fr: (Alice allait dire : << J'en ai goute une fois -- >> mais elle se reprit vivement, et dit : << Non, jamais. >>)

eng: "--so you can have no idea what a delightful thing a Lobster Quadrille is!"
fr: << De sorte que vous ne pouvez pas du tout vous figurer quelle chose delicieuse c'est qu'un quadrille de homards. >>

eng: "No, indeed," said Alice.
fr: << Non, vraiment, >> dit Alice.

eng: "What sort of a dance is it?"
fr: << Qu'est-ce que c'est que cette danse-la ? >>

eng: "Why," said the Gryphon, "you first form into a line along the sea-shore--"
fr: << D'abord, >> dit le Griffon, << on se met en rang le long des bords de la mer -- >>

eng: "Two lines!" cried the Mock Turtle.
fr: << On forme deux rangs, >> cria la Fausse-Tortue :

eng: "Seals, turtles, salmon, and so on; then, when you've cleared all the jelly-fish out of the way--"
fr: des phoques, des tortues et des saumons, et ainsi de suite. Puis lorsqu'on a debarrasse la cote des gelees de mer -- >>

eng: "_That_ generally takes some time," interrupted the Gryphon.
fr: << Cela prend ordinairement longtemps, >> dit le Griffon.

eng: " --you advance twice--"
fr: << --on avance deux fois -- >>

eng: "Each with a lobster as a partner!" cried the Gryphon.
fr: << Chacun ayant un homard pour danseur, >> cria le Griffon.

eng: "Of course," the Mock Turtle said: "advance twice, set to partners--"
fr: << Cela va sans dire, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue. << Avancez deux fois et balancez -- >>

eng: "--change lobsters, and retire in same order," continued the Gryphon.
fr: << Changez de homards, et revenez dans le meme ordre, >> continua le Griffon.

eng: "Then, you know," the Mock Turtle went on, "you throw the--"
fr: << Et puis, vous comprenez, >> continua la Fausse-Tortue, << vous jetez les -- >>

eng: "The lobsters!" shouted the Gryphon, with a bound into the air.
fr: << Les homards ! >> cria le Griffon, en faisant un bond en l'air.

eng: " --as far out to sea as you can--"
fr: << --aussi loin a la mer que vous le pouvez -- >>

eng: "Swim after them!" screamed the Gryphon.
fr: << Vous nagez a leur poursuite ! ! ~~~ >> cria le Griffon.

eng: "Turn a somersault in the sea!" cried the Mock Turtle, capering wildly about.
fr: << --vous faites une cabriole dans la mer ! ~~~ !! >> cria la Fausse-Tortue, en cabriolant de tous cotes comme une folle.

eng: "Change lobsters again!" yelled the Gryphon at the top of its voice.
fr: << Changez encore de homards ! ~~~ !!! >> hurla le Griffon de toutes ses forces.

eng: "Back to land again, and that's all the first figure," said the Mock Turtle, suddenly dropping his voice; and the two creatures, who had been jumping about like mad things all this time, sat down again very sadly and quietly, and looked at Alice.
fr: << --revenez a terre ; et -- c'est la la premiere figure, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue, baissant tout a coup la voix ; et ces deux etres, qui pendant tout ce temps avaient bondi de tous cotes comme des fous, se rassirent bien tristement et bien posement, puis regarderent Alice.

eng: "It must be a very pretty dance," said Alice timidly.
fr: << Cela doit etre une tres-jolie danse, >> dit timidement Alice.

eng: "Would you like to see a little of it?" said the Mock Turtle.
fr: << Voudriez-vous voir un peu comment ca se danse ? >> dit la Fausse-Tortue.

eng: "Very much indeed," said Alice.
fr: << Cela me ferait grand plaisir, >> dit Alice.

eng: "Come, let's try the first figure!" said the Mock Turtle to the Gryphon.
fr: << Allons, essayons la premiere figure, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue au Griffon ;

eng: "We can do without lobsters, you know. Which shall sing?"
fr: << nous pouvons la faire sans homards, vous comprenez. Qui va chanter ? ~~~ >>

eng: "Oh, _you_ sing," said the Gryphon. "I've forgotten the words."
fr: << Oh ! chantez, vous, >> dit le Griffon ; << moi j'ai oublie les paroles. >>

eng: So they began solemnly dancing round and round Alice, every now and then treading on her toes when they passed too close, and waving their forepaws to mark the time, while the Mock Turtle sang this, very slowly and sadly:--
fr: Ils se mirent donc a danser gravement tout autour d'Alice, lui marchant de temps a autre sur les pieds quand ils approchaient trop pres, et remuant leurs pattes de devant pour marquer la mesure, tandis que la Fausse-Tortue chantait tres-lentement et tres-tristement :

eng: "Will you walk a little faster?" said a whiting to a snail.
fr: << Nous n'irons plus a l'eau, Si tu n'avances tot ; Ce Marsouin trop presse Va tous nous ecraser. Colimacon danse, Entre dans la danse ; Sautons, dansons, Avant de faire un plongeon. >>

eng: "There's a porpoise close behind us, and he's treading on my tail. See how eagerly the lobsters and the turtles all advance! They are waiting on the shingle--will you come and join the dance? Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, will you join the dance? Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, won't you join the dance?"
fr: << Je ne veux pas danser, Je me f'rais fracasser. >> << Oh ! ~~~ >> reprend le Merlan, << C'est pourtant bien plaisant. >> Colimacon danse, Entre dans la danse ; Sautons, dansons, Avant de faire un plongeon. << Je ne veux pas plonger, Je ne sais pas nager. >> -- << Le Homard et l'bateau D'sauv'tag' te tir'ront d'l'eau. >> Colimacon danse, Entre dans la danse ; Sautons, dansons, Avant de faire un plongeon.

eng: "You can really have no notion how delightful it will be When they take us up and throw us, with the lobsters, out to sea!"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "But the snail replied "Too far, too far!" and gave a look askance-- Said he thanked the whiting kindly, but he would not join the dance. Would not, could not, would not, could not, would not join the dance. Would not, could not, would not, could not, could not join the dance."
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "What matters it how far we go?" his scaly friend replied. "There is another shore, you know, upon the other side. The further off from England the nearer is to France-- Then turn not pale, beloved snail, but come and join the dance. Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, will you join the dance? Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, won't you join the dance?"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Thank you, it's a very interesting dance to watch," said Alice, feeling very glad that it was over at last: "and I do so like that curious song about the whiting!"
fr: << Merci ; c'est une danse tres-interessante a voir danser, >> dit Alice, enchantee que ce fut enfin fini ; << et je trouve cette curieuse chanson du merlan si agreable ! >>

eng: "Oh, as to the whiting," said the Mock Turtle, "they--you've seen them, of course?"
fr: << Oh ! quant aux merlans, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue, << ils -- vous les avez vus, sans doute ? >>

eng: "Yes," said Alice, "I've often seen them at dinn--" she checked herself hastily.
fr: << Oui, >> dit Alice, << je les ai souvent vus a di-- >> elle s'arreta tout court.

eng: "I don't know where Dinn may be," said the Mock Turtle, "but if you've seen them so often, of course you know what they're like."
fr: << Je ne sais pas ou est Di, >> reprit la Fausse Tortue ; << mais, puisque vous les avez vus si souvent, vous devez savoir l'air qu'ils ont ? >>

eng: "I believe so," Alice replied thoughtfully. "They have their tails in their mouths--and they're all over crumbs."
fr: << Je le crois, >> repliqua Alice, en se recueillant. << Ils ont la queue dans la bouche -- et sont tout couverts de mie de pain. >>

eng: "You're wrong about the crumbs," said the Mock Turtle: "crumbs would all wash off in the sea. But they _have_ their tails in their mouths; and the reason is--" here the Mock Turtle yawned and shut his eyes.--"Tell her about the reason and all that," he said to the Gryphon.
fr: << Vous vous trompez a l'endroit de la mie de pain, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue : << la mie serait enlevee dans la mer, mais ils ont bien la queue dans la bouche, et la raison en est que -- >> Ici la Fausse-Tortue bailla et ferma les yeux. << Dites-lui-en la raison et tout ce qui s'ensuit, >> dit-elle au Griffon.

eng: "The reason is," said the Gryphon, "that they _would_ go with the lobsters to the dance. So they got thrown out to sea. So they had to fall a long way. So they got their tails fast in their mouths. So they couldn't get them out again. That's all."
fr: << La raison, c'est que les merlans, >> dit le Griffon, << voulurent absolument aller a la danse avec les homards. Alors on les jeta a la mer. Alors ils eurent a tomber bien loin, bien loin. Alors ils s'entrerent la queue fortement dans la bouche. Alors ils ne purent plus l'en retirer. Voila tout. >>

eng: "Thank you," said Alice, "it's very interesting. I never knew so much about a whiting before."
fr: << Merci, >> dit Alice, << c'est tres-interessant ; je n'en avais jamais tant appris sur le compte des merlans. >>

eng: "I can tell you more than that, if you like," said the Gryphon.
fr: << Je propose donc, >> dit le Griffon, << que vous nous racontiez quelques-unes de vos aventures. >>

eng: "Do you know why it's called a whiting?"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "I never thought about it," said Alice. "Why?"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "_It does the boots and shoes_," the Gryphon replied very solemnly.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: Alice was thoroughly puzzled.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Does the boots and shoes!" she repeated in a wondering tone.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Why, what are _your_ shoes done with?" said the Gryphon.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "I mean, what makes them so shiny?" Alice looked down at them, and considered a little before she gave her answer. "They're done with blacking, I believe."
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Boots and shoes under the sea," the Gryphon went on in a deep voice, "are done with a whiting. Now you know."
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "And what are they made of?" Alice asked in a tone of great curiosity.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Soles and eels, of course," the Gryphon replied rather impatiently: "any shrimp could have told you that."
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "If I'd been the whiting," said Alice, whose thoughts were still running on the song, "I'd have said to the porpoise, 'Keep back, please: we don't want _you_ with us!'"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "They were obliged to have him with them," the Mock Turtle said: "no wise fish would go anywhere without a porpoise."
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Wouldn't it really?" said Alice in a tone of great surprise.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Of course not," said the Mock Turtle: "why, if a fish came to _me_, and told me he was going a journey, I should say 'With what porpoise?'"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Don't you mean 'purpose'?" said Alice.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "I mean what I say," the Mock Turtle replied in an offended tone. And the Gryphon added "Come, let's hear some of _your_ adventures."
fr: << I mean what I say, >> the Mock Turtle replied in an offended tone. And the Gryphon added "Come, let's hear some of _your_ adventures."

eng: "I could tell you my adventures--beginning from this morning," said Alice a little timidly: "but it's no use going back to yesterday, because I was a different person then."
fr: << Je pourrais vous conter mes aventures a partir de ce matin, >> dit Alice un peu timidement ; << mais il est inutile de parler de la journee d'hier, car j'etais une personne tout a fait differente alors. >>

eng: "Explain all that," said the Mock Turtle.
fr: << Expliquez-nous cela, >> dit la Fausse-Tortue.

eng: "No, no! The adventures first," said the Gryphon in an impatient tone: "explanations take such a dreadful time."'
fr: << Non, non, les aventures d'abord, >> dit le Griffon d'un ton d'impatience ; << les explications prennent tant de temps.

eng: "It all came different!"
fr: "<< Tout de travers, >>"

eng: the Mock Turtle repeated thoughtfully.
fr: repeta la Fausse-Tortue d'un air reveur.

eng: "I should like to hear her try and repeat something now.
fr: << Je voudrais bien l'entendre reciter quelque chose a present.

eng: Tell her to begin."
fr: Dites-lui de s'y mettre. >>

eng: He looked at the Gryphon as if he thought it had some kind of authority over Alice.
fr: Elle regardait le Griffon comme si elle lui croyait de l'autorite sur Alice.

eng: "Stand up and repeat ''_Tis the voice of the sluggard_,'"
fr: << Debout, et recitez : << C'est la voix du canon, >>

eng: said the Gryphon.
fr: dit le Griffon.

eng: "How the creatures order one about, and make one repeat lessons!"
fr: << Comme ces etres-la vous commandent et vous font repeter des lecons !'

eng: However, she got up, and began to repeat it, but her head was so full of the Lobster Quadrille, that she hardly knew what she was saying, and the words came very queer indeed:--
fr: Cependant elle se leva et se mit a reciter ; mais elle avait la tete si pleine du Quadrille de Homards, qu'elle savait a peine ce qu'elle disait, et que les mots lui venaient tout drolement : --

eng: "'Tis the voice of the Lobster; I heard him declare, "You have baked me too brown, I must sugar my hair."
fr: << C'est la voix du homard grondant comme la foudre : << On m'a trop fait bouillir, il faut que je me poudre ! >>

eng: As a duck with its eyelids, so he with his nose Trims his belt and his buttons, and turns out his toes."
fr: Puis, les pieds en dehors, prenant la brosse en main, De se faire bien beau vite il se met en train. >>

eng: [later editions continued as follows When the sands are all dry, he is gay as a lark, And will talk in contemptuous tones of the Shark, But, when the tide rises and sharks are around, His voice has a timid and tremulous sound.]
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "That's different from what _I_ used to say when I was a child," said the Gryphon.
fr: << C'est tout different de ce que je recitais quand j'etais petit, moi, >> dit le Griffon.

eng: "She can't explain it," said the Gryphon hastily.
fr: "<< Elle ne peut pas l'expliquer, >> dit le Griffon vivement.

eng: "Go on with the next verse."
fr: "<< Continuez, recitez les vers suivants. >>

eng: "But about his toes?" the Mock Turtle persisted.
fr: "<< Mais, les pieds en dehors, >> continua opiniatrement la Fausse-Tortue.

eng: "How _could_ he turn them out with his nose, you know?"
fr: "<< Pourquoi dire qu'il avait les pieds en dehors ? >>

eng: "It's the first position in dancing." Alice said; but was dreadfully puzzled by the whole thing, and longed to change the subject.
fr: "<< C'est la premiere position lorsqu'on apprend a danser, >> dit Alice ; tout cela l'embarrassait fort, et il lui tardait de changer la conversation.

eng: "Go on with the next verse," the Gryphon repeated impatiently: "it begins '_I passed by his garden_.'"
fr: "<< Recitez les vers suivants, >> repeta le Griffon avec impatience ; << ca commence : << Passant pres de chez lui -- >> >>

eng: Alice did not dare to disobey, though she felt sure it would all come wrong, and she went on in a trembling voice:-- "I passed by his garden, and marked, with one eye, How the Owl and the Panther were sharing a pie--" [later editions continued as follows The Panther took pie-crust, and gravy, and meat, While the Owl had the dish as its share of the treat. When the pie was all finished, the Owl, as a boon, Was kindly permitted to pocket the spoon: While the Panther received knife and fork with a growl, And concluded the banquet--]
fr: Alice n'osa pas desobeir, bien qu'elle fut sure que les mots allaient lui venir tout de travers. Elle continua donc d'une voix tremblante : << Passant pres de chez lui, j'ai vu, ne vous deplaise, Une huitre et un hibou qui dinaient fort a l'aise. ~~~ >>

eng: "What _is_ the use of repeating all that stuff," the Mock Turtle interrupted, "if you don't explain it as you go on? It's by far the most confusing thing _I_ ever heard!"
fr: "<< A quoi bon repeter tout ce galimatias, >> interrompit la Fausse-Tortue, << si vous ne l'expliquez pas a mesure que vous le dites ? C'est, de beaucoup, ce que j'ai entendu de plus embrouillant.

eng: "Or would you like the Mock Turtle to sing you a song?"
fr: "<< Ou bien, preferez-vous que la Fausse-Tortue vous chante quelque chose ? >>"

eng: "Oh, a song, please, if the Mock Turtle would be so kind," Alice replied, so eagerly that the Gryphon said, in a rather offended tone,
fr: "<< Oh ! une chanson, je vous prie ; si la Fausse-Tortue veut bien avoir cette obligeance, >> repondit Alice, avec tant d'empressement que le Griffon dit d'un air un peu offense :"

eng: "Hm! No accounting for tastes! Sing her '_Turtle Soup_,' will you, old fellow?"
fr: "<< Hum ! Chacun son gout. Chantez-lui << La Soupe a la Tortue, >> he ! camarade ! >>"

eng: The Mock Turtle sighed deeply, and began, in a voice sometimes choked with sobs, to sing this:--
fr: La Fausse-Tortue poussa un profond soupir et commenca, d'une voix de temps en temps etouffee par les sanglots :

eng: "Beautiful Soup, so rich and green, Waiting in a hot tureen! ~~~ Who for such dainties would not stoop? Soup of the evening, beautiful Soup! Soup of the evening, beautiful Soup! Beau--ootiful Soo--oop! Beau--ootiful Soo--oop! ~~~ Soo--oop of the e--e--evening, Beautiful, beautiful Soup!"
fr: "<< O doux potage, O mets delicieux ! Ah ! ~~~ pour partage, Quoi de plus precieux ? Plonger dans ma soupiere Cette vaste cuillere Est un bonheur Qui me rejouit le coeur. << Gibier, volaille, Lievres, dindes, perdreaux, Rien qui te vaille, -- Pas meme les pruneaux ! Plonger dans ma soupiere Cette vaste cuillere Est un bonheur Qui me rejouit le coeur. >>"

eng: "Beautiful Soup! Who cares for fish, Game, or any other dish? Who would not give all else for two p ennyworth only of beautiful Soup? Pennyworth only of beautiful Soup? ~~~ Beau--ootiful Soo--oop! Beau--ootiful Soo--oop! ~~~ Soo--oop of the e--e--evening, Beautiful, beauti--FUL SOUP!"
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: "Chorus again!"
fr: "<< Bis au refrain !' "

eng: cried the Gryphon, and, taking Alice by the hand, it hurried off, without waiting for the end of the song.
fr: >> cria le Griffon ; et, prenant Alice par la main, il se mit a courir sans attendre la fin de la chanson.

eng: "What trial is it?" Alice panted as she ran;
fr: << Qu'est-ce que c'est que ce proces ? >> demanda Alice hors d'haleine ;

eng: but the Gryphon only answered "Come on!"
fr: mais le Griffon se contenta de repondre : << Venez donc ! >>

eng: and ran the faster, while more and more faintly came, carried on the breeze that followed them, the melancholy words:-- "Soo--oop of the e--e--evening, Beautiful, beautiful Soup!"
fr: en courant de plus belle, tandis que leur parvenaient, de plus en plus faibles, apportees par la brise qui les poursuivait, ces paroles pleines de melancolie : << Plonger dans ma soupiere Cette vaste cuillere Est un bonheur Qui me rejouit le coeur. >>

eng: CHAPTER XI.
fr: CHAPITRE XI.

eng: The King and Queen of Hearts were seated on their throne when they arrived, with a great crowd assembled about them--all sorts of little birds and beasts, as well as the whole pack of cards:
fr: Le Roi et la Reine de Coeur etaient assis sur leur trone, entoures d'une nombreuse assemblee : toutes sortes de petits oiseaux et d'autres betes, ainsi que le paquet de cartes tout entier.

eng: the Knave was standing before them, in chains, with a soldier on each side to guard him;
fr: Le Valet, charge de chaines, garde de chaque cote par un soldat, se tenait debout devant le trone,

eng: and near the King was the White Rabbit, with a trumpet in one hand, and a scroll of parchment in the other.
fr: et pres du roi se trouvait le Lapin Blanc, tenant d'une main une trompette et de l'autre un rouleau de parchemin.

eng: In the very middle of the court was a table, with a large dish of tarts upon it:
fr: Au beau milieu de la salle etait une table sur laquelle on voyait un grand plat de tartes ;

eng: they looked so good, that it made Alice quite hungry to look at them--
fr: ces tartes semblaient si bonnes que cela donna faim a Alice, rien que de les regarder.

eng: "I wish they'd get the trial done," she thought, "and hand round the refreshments!"
fr: << Je voudrais bien qu'on se depechat de finir le proces, >> pensa-t-elle, << et qu'on fit passer les rafraichissements, >>

eng: But there seemed to be no chance of this, so she began looking at everything about her, to pass away the time.
fr: mais cela ne paraissait guere probable, aussi se mit-elle a regarder tout autour d'elle pour passer le temps.

eng: Alice could see, as well as if she were looking over their shoulders, that all the jurors were writing down "stupid things!" on their slates, and she could even make out that one of them didn't know how to spell "stupid," and that he had to ask his neighbour to tell him.
fr: Alice pouvait voir, aussi clairement que si elle eut regarde par-dessus leurs epaules, que tous les jures etaient en train d'ecrire << les niais >> sur leurs ardoises, et elle pouvait meme distinguer que l'un d'eux ne savait pas ecrire << niais >> et qu'il etait oblige de le demander a son voisin.

eng: "A nice muddle their slates'll be in before the trial's over!" thought Alice.
fr: << Leurs ardoises seront dans un bel etat avant la fin du proces ! >> pensa Alice.

eng: One of the jurors had a pencil that squeaked.
fr: Un des jures avait un crayon qui grincait ;

eng: This of course, Alice could _not_ stand, and she went round the court and got behind him, and very soon found an opportunity of taking it away.
fr: Alice, vous le pensez bien, ne pouvait pas souffrir cela ; elle fit le tour de la salle, arriva derriere lui, et trouva bientot l'occasion d'enlever le crayon.

eng: She did it so quickly that the poor little juror (it was Bill, the Lizard) could not make out at all what had become of it; so, after hunting all about for it, he was obliged to write with one finger for the rest of the day; and this was of very little use, as it left no mark on the slate.
fr: Ce fut si tot fait que le pauvre petit jure (c'etait Jacques, le lezard) ne pouvait pas s'imaginer ce qu'il etait devenu. Apres avoir cherche partout, il fut oblige d'ecrire avec un doigt tout le reste du jour, et cela etait fort inutile, puisque son doigt ne laissait aucune marque sur l'ardoise.

eng: "Herald, read the accusation!"
fr: << Heraut, lisez l'acte d'accusation !

eng: 'On this the White Rabbit blew three blasts on the trumpet, and then unrolled the parchment scroll, and read as follows:-- "The Queen of Hearts, she made some tarts, All on a summer day: The Knave of Hearts, he stole those tarts, And took them quite away!"'
fr: 'Sur ce, le Lapin Blanc sonna trois fois de la trompette, et puis, deroulant le parchemin, lut ainsi qu'il suit : << La Reine de Coeur fit des tartes, Un beau jour de printemps ; Le Valet de Coeur prit les tartes, Et s'en fut tout content ! >>'

eng: '"Consider your verdict," the King said to the jury.'
fr: '<< Deliberez, >> dit le Roi aux jures.'

eng: '"Not yet, not yet!" the Rabbit hastily interrupted. "There's a great deal to come before that!"'
fr: '<< Pas encore, pas encore, >> interrompit vivement le Lapin ; << il y a bien des choses a faire auparavant ! >>'

eng: '"Call the first witness," said the King; and the White Rabbit blew three blasts on the trumpet, and called out, "First witness!"'
fr: '<< Appelez les temoins, >> dit le Roi ; et le Lapin Blanc sonna trois fois de la trompette, et cria : << Le premier temoin !'

eng: "Fifteenth," said the March Hare.
fr: "<< Le Quinze ! ~~~ >> dit le Lievre.

eng: "Sixteenth," added the Dormouse.
fr: "<< Le Seize ! >> ajouta le Loir.

eng: "Write that down," the King said to the jury,
fr: "<< Notez cela, >> dit le Roi aux jures.

eng: and the jury eagerly wrote down all three dates on their slates, and then added them up, and reduced the answer to shillings and pence.
fr: Et les jures s'empresserent d'ecrire les trois dates sur leurs ardoises ; puis en firent l'addition, dont ils chercherent a reduire le total en francs et centimes.

eng: "Take off your hat," the King said to the Hatter.
fr: "<< Otez votre chapeau, >> dit le Roi au Chapelier.

eng: "_Stolen!_" the King exclaimed, turning to the jury, who instantly made a memorandum of the fact.
fr: "<< Vole ! ~~~ >> s'ecria le Roi en se tournant du cote des jures, qui s'empresserent de prendre note du fait.

eng: "I keep them to sell," the Hatter added as an explanation;
fr: "<< Je les tiens en vente, >> ajouta le Chapelier, comme explication.

eng: "I've none of my own. I'm a hatter."
fr: "<< Je n'en ai pas a moi ; je suis chapelier. >>

eng: Here the Queen put on her spectacles, and began staring at the Hatter, who turned pale and fidgeted.
fr: Ici la Reine mit ses lunettes, et se prit a regarder fixement le Chapelier, qui devint pale et tremblant.

eng: 'Just at this moment Alice felt a very curious sensation, which puzzled her a good deal until she made out what it was: she was beginning to grow larger again, and she thought at first she would get up and leave the court; but on second thoughts she decided to remain where she was as long as there was room for her.'
fr: 'Juste a ce moment-la, Alice eprouva une etrange sensation qui l'embarrassa beaucoup, jusqu'a ce qu'elle se fut rendu compte de ce que c'etait. Elle recommencait a grandir, et elle pensa d'abord a se lever et a quitter la cour : mais, toute reflexion faite, elle se decida a rester ou elle etait, tant qu'il y aurait de la place pour elle.'

eng: '"I wish you wouldn't squeeze so." said the Dormouse, who was sitting next to her. "I can hardly breathe."'
fr: '<< Ne poussez donc pas comme ca, >> dit le Loir ; << je puis a peine respirer. >>'

eng: '"I can't help it," said Alice very meekly: "I'm growing."'
fr: '<< Ce n'est pas de ma faute, >> dit Alice doucement ; << je grandis.'

eng: "It began with the tea," the Hatter replied.
fr: "<< Ca a commence par le the, >> repondit le Chapelier.

eng: "Of course twinkling begins with a T!" said the King sharply.
fr: << Je vous dis que dragee commence par un d ! >> cria le Roi vivement.

eng: "Do you take me for a dunce? Go on!"
fr: << Me prenez-vous pour un ane ? Continuez ! >>

eng: "I'm a poor man," the Hatter went on, "and most things twinkled after that--only the March Hare said--"
fr: << Je suis un pauvre homme, >> continua le Chapelier ; << et les dragees et les autres choses me firent perdre la tete. Mais le Lievre dit -- >>

eng: "I didn't!" the March Hare interrupted in a great hurry.
fr: << C'est faux ! >> s'ecria le Lievre se depechant de l'interrompre.

eng: "You did!" said the Hatter.
fr: << C'est vrai ! ~~~ >> cria le Chapelier.

eng: "I deny it!" said the March Hare.
fr: << Je le nie ! >> cria le Lievre.

eng: "He denies it," said the King: "leave out that part."'
fr: << Il le nie ! >> dit le Roi. << Passez la-dessus. ~~~ >>

eng: (No direct equivalent in text)
fr: << Eh bien !'

eng: "After that," continued the Hatter, "I cut some more bread-and-butter--"
fr: "<< Apres cela, >> continua le Chapelier, << je me coupai d'autres tartines de beurre. >>

eng: "But what did the Dormouse say?" one of the jury asked.
fr: "<< Mais, que dit le Loir ? >> demanda un des jures.

eng: "That I can't remember," said the Hatter.
fr: "<< C'est ce que je ne peux pas me rappeler, >> dit le Chapelier."

eng: The miserable Hatter dropped his teacup and bread-and-butter, and went down on one knee.
fr: >> Le malheureux Chapelier laissa tomber sa tasse et sa tartine de beurre, et mit un genou en terre.

eng: "I'm a poor man, your Majesty," he began.
fr: >> Je suis un pauvre homme, Votre Majeste ! >> commenca-t-il.

eng: "You're a _very_ poor _speaker_," said the King.
fr: >> Vous etes un tres-pauvre orateur, >> dit le Roi.

eng: "I've so often read in the newspapers, at the end of trials, "There was some attempts at applause, which was immediately suppressed by the officers of the court," and I never understood what it meant till now."
fr: "<< J'ai souvent lu dans les journaux, a la fin des proces : << Il se fit quelques tentatives d'applaudissements qui furent bientot reprimees par les huissiers, >> et je n'avais jamais compris jusqu'a present ce que cela voulait dire. >>

eng: "If that's all you know about it, you may stand down," continued the King.
fr: "<< Si c'est la tout ce que vous savez de l'affaire, vous pouvez vous prosterner, >> continua le Roi.

eng: "I can't go no lower," said the Hatter: "I'm on the floor, as it is."
fr: "<< Je ne puis pas me prosterner plus bas que cela, >> dit le Chapelier ; << je suis deja par terre.

eng: "--and just take his head off outside," the Queen added to one of the officers:
fr: "<< Et coupez-lui la tete dehors, >> ajouta la Reine, s'adressant a un des huissiers ;

eng: but the Hatter was out of sight before the officer could get to the door.
fr: mais le Chapelier etait deja bien loin avant que l'huissier arrivat a la porte.

eng: "Call the next witness!"
fr: "<< Appelez un autre temoin, >> dit le Roi.

eng: said the King.
fr: (No direct equivalent in text)

eng: The next witness was the Duchess's cook.
fr: L'autre temoin, c'etait la cuisiniere de la Duchesse ;

eng: She carried the pepper-box in her hand, and Alice guessed who it was, even before she got into the court, by the way the people near the door began sneezing all at once.
fr: elle tenait la poivriere a la main, et Alice devina qui c'etait, meme avant qu'elle entrat dans la salle, en voyant eternuer, tout a coup et tous a la fois, les gens qui se trouvaient pres de la porte.

eng: "Give your evidence," said the King.
fr: << Faites votre deposition, >> dit le Roi.

eng: "Shan't," said the cook.
fr: << Non ! ~~~ >> dit la cuisiniere.

eng: The King looked anxiously at the White Rabbit,
fr: Le Roi regarda d'un air inquiet le Lapin Blanc,

eng: who said in a low voice, "Your Majesty must cross-examine _this_ witness."'
fr: qui lui dit a voix basse : << Il faut que Votre Majeste interroge ce temoin-la contradictoirement.'

eng: "Pepper, mostly," said the cook.
fr: '>> << De poivre principalement ! >> dit la cuisiniere.

eng: "Treacle," said a sleepy voice behind her.
fr: << De melasse, >> dit une voix endormie derriere elle.

eng: "Collar that Dormouse," the Queen shrieked out.
fr: << Saisissez ce Loir au collet ! >> cria la Reine.

eng: "Behead that Dormouse! Turn that Dormouse out of court! Suppress him! Pinch him! Off with his whiskers!"
fr: << Coupez la tete a ce Loir ! Mettez ce Loir a la porte ! Reprimez-le, pincez-le, arrachez-lui ses moustaches ! >>

eng: For some minutes the whole court was in confusion, getting the Dormouse turned out, and, by the time they had settled down again, the cook had disappeared.
fr: Pendant quelques instants, toute la cour fut sens dessus dessous pour mettre le Loir a la porte ; et, quand le calme fut retabli, la cuisiniere avait disparu.

eng: "Never mind!" said the King, with an air of great relief.
fr: << Cela ne fait rien, >> dit le Roi, comme soulage d'un grand poids.
